@node TR_OPTMGMT_ACK
@subsubsection Transaction Options Management Acknowledgement

@subsubheading @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_ACK}

This primitive indicates to the transaction user that the options management request has completed.

@subsubheading Format

The format of the message is one @prim{M_PCPROTO} message block structured as follows:

@display
@verbatim
typedef struct TR_optmgmt_ack {
    ulong PRIM_type;          /* Always TR_OPTMGMT_ACK */
    ulong OPT_length;         /* options length */
    ulong OPT_offset;         /* options offset */
    ulong MGMT_flags;         /* options data flags */
} TR_optmgmt_ack_t;
@end verbatim
@tpindex TR_optmgmt_ack_t
@end display

@subsubheading Parameters

The primitive has the following arguments:

@table @parm

@item PRIM_type
Indicates the primitive type.  Always @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_ACK}.

@item OPT_length
Indicates the length of the protocol options associated with the primitive.

@item OPT_offset
Indicates the offset from the beginning of the @manref{M_PCPROTO(9)} message block where the options
begin.  The proper alignment of the options is not guaranteed.

@item MGMT_flags
Indicates the management flags in the same form as specified in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive,
@xref{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ}, with any additional flags as specified below.

@end table

@subsubheading Flags

The flags returned in @parm{MGMT_flags} represents the single most severe result of the operation.
The flags returned will be one of the following values (in order of decreasing severity):

@table @pval

@item TR_NOTSUPPORT
This flag indicates that at least one of the options specified in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ}
primitive was not supported by the trasnaction provider at the current privilege level of the
requesting user.

@item TR_READONLY
This flag indicates that at least one of the options specified in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ}
primitive is read-only (for the current TRI state).  This flag does not apply when the
@parm{MGMT_flags} field in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive was @pval{T_DEFAULT}.

@item TR_FAILURE
This flag indicates that negotiation of at least one of the options specified in the
@prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive failed.  This is not used for illegal format or values.  This flag
does not apply when the @parm{MGMT_flags} field in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive was
@pval{T_DEFAULT} or @pval{T_CURRENT}.

@item TR_PARTSUCCESS
This flag indicates that the negotiation of at least one of the options specified in the
@prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive was negotiated to a value of lesser quality than the value
requested.  This flag only applies when the @parm{MGMT_flags} field of the @prim{TR_OPGMGMT_REQ}
primitive was @pval{T_NEGOTIATE}.

@item TR_SUCCESS
This flag indicates that all of the specified options were negoitated or returned successfully.

@end table

@subsubheading Mode

This primitive is valid in both unidirectional and bidirectional modes.

@subsubheading Originator

This primitive is originated by the TR provider.

@subsubheading Valid State

This primitive is issued in response to a @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive and is valid in any state.

@subsubheading New State

The new state remains unchanged.

@subsubheading Rules

The following rules apply to the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_ACK} primitive:

@itemize ---

@item If the value of @parm{MGMT_flags} in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive is @pval{TR_DEFAULT},
the provider should return the default provider options without changing the existing options
associated with the @dfn{Stream}.

@item If the value of @parm{MGMT_flags} in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive is @pval{TR_CHECK},
the provider should return the options as specified in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive along
with the additional flags @pval{TR_SUCCESS} or @pval{TR_FAILURE} which indicate to the user whether
the specified options are supportable by the provider.  The provider should not change any existing
options associated with the @dfn{Stream}.

@item If the value of @parm{MGMT_flags} in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive is
@pval{TR_NEGOTIATE}, the provider should set and negotiate the option as specified by the following
rules:

@itemize @minus

@item If the @parm{OPT_length} field of the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive is zero (@samp{0}), then
the transaction provider is to set and return the default options associated with the @dfn{Stream}
in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_ACK} primitive.

@item If options are specified in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive, then the transaction provider
should negotiate those options, set the negotiated options and return the negotiated options in the
@prim{TR_OPTMGMT_ACK} pirmitive.  It is the user's responsibility to check the negotiated options
returned in the @prim{TR_OPMGMT_ACK} primitive and take appropriate action.

@end itemize

@item If the value of @parm{MGMT_flags} in the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primtiive is @pval{TR_CURRENT},
the provider should return the currently effective option values without changing any existing
options associated with the @dfn{Stream}.

@end itemize

@subsubheading Errors

If the above rules result in an error condition, the transaction provider must issue a
@prim{TR_ERROR_ACK} primitive (@pxref{TR_ERROR_ACK}) to the transaction user specifying the error as
defined in the description of the @prim{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ} primitive (@pxref{TR_OPTMGMT_REQ}).

